# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: mojo-lang
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:mojo-lang/just-in-time-compilation] JIT compilation is a combination of the two traditional approaches to translation to machine code: ahead-of-time compilation (AOT), and interpretation, which combines some advantages and drawbacks of both.
[src:mojo-lang/just-in-time-compilation] Roughly, JIT compilation combines the speed of compiled code with the flexibility of interpretation, with the overhead of an interpreter and the additional overhead of compiling and linking (not just interpreting).
[src:mojo-lang/just-in-time-compilation] JIT compilation is a form of dynamic compilation, and allows adaptive optimization such as dynamic recompilation and microarchitecture-specific speedups.
[src:mojo-lang/just-in-time-compilation] Interpretation and JIT compilation are particularly suited for dynamic programming languages, as the runtime system can handle late-bound data types and enforce security guarantees.
[src:mojo-lang/just-in-time-compilation] The earliest published JIT compiler is generally attributed to work on LISP by John McCarthy in 1960.
[src:mojo-lang/just-in-time-compilation] Another early example was by Ken Thompson, who in 1968 gave one of the first applications of regular expressions, here for pattern matching in the text editor QED.
[src:mojo-lang/just-in-time-compilation] For speed, Thompson implemented regular expression matching by JITing to IBM 7094 code on the Compatible Time-Sharing System.
[src:mojo-lang/just-in-time-compilation] An influential technique for deriving compiled code from interpretation was pioneered by James G.
[src:mojo-lang/just-in-time-compilation] Mitchell in 1970, which he implemented for the experimental language *LC²*.
[src:mojo-lang/just-in-time-compilation] 1980) pioneered new aspects of JIT compilations.
[src:mojo-lang/just-in-time-compilation] For example, translation to machine code was done on demand, and the result was cached for later use.
[src:mojo-lang/just-in-time-compilation] When memory became scarce, the system would delete some of this code and regenerate it when it was needed again.
[src:mojo-lang/just-in-time-compilation] Sun's Self language improved these techniques extensively and was at one point the fastest Smalltalk system in the world, achieving up to half the speed of optimized C but with a fully object-oriented programming language.
[src:mojo-lang/just-in-time-compilation] Self was abandoned by Sun, but the research went into the Java language.
[src:mojo-lang/just-in-time-compilation] The term "Just-in-time compilation" was borrowed from the manufacturing term "Just in time" and popularized by Java, with James Gosling using the term from 1993.
[src:mojo-lang/just-in-time-compilation] Currently JITing is used by most implementations of the Java virtual machine, as HotSpot builds on, and extensively uses, this research base.
[src:mojo-lang/just-in-time-compilation] The HP project Dynamo was an experimental JIT compiler where the "bytecode" format and the machine code format were the same; the system optimized PA-8000 machine code.
[src:mojo-lang/just-in-time-compilation] In November 2020, PHP 8.0 introduced a JIT compiler.
[src:mojo-lang/just-in-time-compilation] In October 2024, CPython introduced an experimental JIT compiler.
[src:mojo-lang/just-in-time-compilation] In a bytecode-compiled system, source code is translated to an intermediate representation known as bytecode.
[src:mojo-lang/just-in-time-compilation] Bytecode is not the machine code for any particular computer, and may be portable among computer architectures.
[src:mojo-lang/just-in-time-compilation] The bytecode may then be interpreted by, or run on a virtual machine.
[src:mojo-lang/just-in-time-compilation] The JIT compiler reads the bytecodes in many sections (or in full, rarely) and compiles them dynamically into machine code so the program can run faster.
[src:mojo-lang/just-in-time-compilation] This can be done per-file, per-function or even on any arbitrary code fragment; the code can be compiled when it is about to be executed (hence the name "just-in-time"), and then cached and reused later without needing to be recompiled.
[src:mojo-lang/just-in-time-compilation] By contrast, a traditional *interpreted virtual machine* will simply interpret the bytecode, generally with much lower performance.
[src:mojo-lang/just-in-time-compilation] Some *interpreter*s even interpret source code, without the step of first compiling to bytecode, with even worse performance.
[src:mojo-lang/just-in-time-compilation] *Statically-compiled code* or *native code* is compiled prior to deployment.
[src:mojo-lang/just-in-time-compilation] A *dynamic compilation environment* is one in which the compiler can be used during execution.
[src:mojo-lang/just-in-time-compilation] The deployed bytecode is portable, unlike native code.
[src:mojo-lang/just-in-time-compilation] Since the runtime has control over the compilation, like interpreted bytecode, it can run in a secure sandbox.
[src:mojo-lang/just-in-time-compilation] Compilers from bytecode to machine code are easier to write, because the portable bytecode compiler has already done much of the work.
[src:mojo-lang/just-in-time-compilation] JIT code generally offers far better performance than interpreters.
[src:mojo-lang/just-in-time-compilation] The system is able to collect statistics about how the program is actually running in the environment it is in, and it can rearrange and recompile for optimum performance.
[src:mojo-lang/just-in-time-compilation] However, some static compilers can also take profile information as input.
[src:mojo-lang/just-in-time-compilation] The system can do global code optimizations (e.g. inlining of library functions) without losing the advantages of dynamic linking and without the overheads inherent to static compilers and linkers.
[src:mojo-lang/just-in-time-compilation] With just-in-time compilation in many cases this processing can be moved out of loops, often giving large increases of speed.
[src:mojo-lang/just-in-time-compilation] Although this is possible with statically compiled garbage collected languages, a bytecode system can more easily rearrange executed code for better cache utilization.
[src:mojo-lang/just-in-time-compilation] However, a special type of "JIT" may potentially *not* target the physical machine's CPU architecture, but rather an optimized VM bytecode where limitations on raw machine code prevail, especially where that bytecode's VM eventually leverages a JIT to native code.
[src:mojo-lang/just-in-time-compilation] JIT causes a slight to noticeable delay in the initial execution of an application, due to the time taken to load and compile the input code.
[src:mojo-lang/just-in-time-compilation] Sometimes this delay is called "startup time delay" or "warm-up time".
[src:mojo-lang/just-in-time-compilation] In general, the more optimization JIT performs, the better the code it will generate, but the initial delay will also increase.
[src:mojo-lang/just-in-time-compilation] A JIT compiler therefore has to make a trade-off between the compilation time and the quality of the code it hopes to generate.
[src:mojo-lang/just-in-time-compilation] Startup time can include increased IO-bound operations in addition to JIT compilation: for example, the *rt.jar* class data file for the Java virtual machine (JVM) is 40 MB and the JVM must seek a lot of data in this contextually huge file.
[src:mojo-lang/just-in-time-compilation] One possible optimization, used by Sun's HotSpot Java virtual machine, is to combine interpretation and JIT compilation.
[src:mojo-lang/just-in-time-compilation] The application code is initially interpreted, but the JVM monitors which sequences of bytecode are frequently executed and translates them to machine code for direct execution on the hardware.
[src:mojo-lang/just-in-time-compilation] For bytecode which is executed only a few times, this saves the compilation time and reduces the initial latency; for frequently executed bytecode, JIT compilation is used to run at high speed, after an initial phase of slow interpretation.
[src:mojo-lang/just-in-time-compilation] Further, since a program spends most time executing a minority of its code, the reduced compilation time is significant.
[src:mojo-lang/just-in-time-compilation] Finally, during the initial code interpretation, execution statistics can be collected before compilation, which helps to perform better optimization.
[src:mojo-lang/just-in-time-compilation] The correct tradeoff can vary due to circumstances.
[src:mojo-lang/just-in-time-compilation] For example, Sun's Java virtual machine has two major modes—client and server.
[src:mojo-lang/just-in-time-compilation] In client mode, minimal compilation and optimization is performed, to reduce startup time.
[src:mojo-lang/just-in-time-compilation] In server mode, extensive compilation and optimization is performed, to maximize performance once the application is running by sacrificing startup time.
[src:mojo-lang/just-in-time-compilation] Other Java just-in-time compilers have used a runtime measurement of the number of times a method has executed combined with the bytecode size of a method as a heuristic to decide when to compile.
[src:mojo-lang/just-in-time-compilation] Still another uses the number of times executed combined with the detection of loops.
[src:mojo-lang/just-in-time-compilation] In general, it is much harder to accurately predict which methods to optimize in short-running applications than in long-running ones.
[src:mojo-lang/just-in-time-compilation] Native Image Generator (Ngen) by Microsoft is another approach at reducing the initial delay.
[src:mojo-lang/just-in-time-compilation] Ngen pre-compiles (or "pre-JITs") bytecode in a Common Intermediate Language image into machine native code.
[src:mojo-lang/just-in-time-compilation] As a result, no runtime compilation is needed. .NET Framework 2.0 shipped with Visual Studio 2005 runs Ngen on all of the Microsoft dynamic-link library (DLL) files right after installing.
[src:mojo-lang/just-in-time-compilation] Pre-jitting provides a way to reduce startup time.
[src:mojo-lang/just-in-time-compilation] However, the quality of code it generates may be lower than the one that is JITed, for the same reasons why code compiled statically, without profile-guided optimization, cannot be as good as JIT compiled code in the extreme case: the lack of profiling data to drive, for instance, inline caching.
[src:mojo-lang/just-in-time-compilation] There also exist Java implementations that combine an AOT (ahead-of-time) compiler with either a JIT compiler (Excelsior JET) or interpreter (GNU Compiler for Java).
[src:mojo-lang/just-in-time-compilation] JIT compilation may not reliably achieve its goal, namely entering a steady state of improved performance after a short initial warmup period.
[src:mojo-lang/just-in-time-compilation] Across eight different virtual machines, Barrett et al.
[src:mojo-lang/just-in-time-compilation] (2017) measured six widely used microbenchmarks which are commonly used by virtual machine implementors as optimisation targets, running them repeatedly within a single process execution.
[src:mojo-lang/just-in-time-compilation] Even where an improved steady-state was reached, it sometimes took many hundreds of iterations.
[src:mojo-lang/just-in-time-compilation] (2022) instead focused on the HotSpot virtual machine but with a much wider array of benchmarks, finding that 10.9% of process executions failed to reach a steady state of performance, and 43.5% of benchmarks did not consistently attain a steady state across multiple executions.
[src:mojo-lang/just-in-time-compilation] JIT compilation fundamentally uses executable data, and thus poses security challenges and possible exploits.
[src:mojo-lang/just-in-time-compilation] Implementation of JIT compilation consists of compiling source code or byte code to machine code and executing it.
[src:mojo-lang/just-in-time-compilation] This is generally done directly in memory: the JIT compiler outputs the machine code directly into memory and immediately executes it, rather than outputting it to disk and then invoking the code as a separate program, as in usual ahead of time compilation.
[src:mojo-lang/just-in-time-compilation] In modern architectures this runs into a problem due to executable space protection: arbitrary memory cannot be executed, as otherwise there is a potential security hole.
[src:mojo-lang/just-in-time-compilation] Thus memory must be marked as executable; for security reasons this should be done *after* the code has been written to memory, and marked read-only, as writable/executable memory is a security hole (see W^X).
[src:mojo-lang/just-in-time-compilation] For instance Firefox's JIT compiler for JavaScript introduced this protection in a release version with Firefox 46.
[src:mojo-lang/just-in-time-compilation] JIT spraying is a class of computer security exploits that use JIT compilation for heap spraying: the resulting memory is then executable, which allows an exploit if execution can be moved into the heap.
[src:mojo-lang/just-in-time-compilation] JIT compilation can be applied to some programs, or can be used for certain capacities, particularly dynamic capacities such as regular expressions.
[src:mojo-lang/just-in-time-compilation] For example, a text editor may compile a regular expression provided at runtime to machine code to allow faster matching: this cannot be done ahead of time, as the pattern is only provided at runtime.
[src:mojo-lang/just-in-time-compilation] Several modern runtime environments rely on JIT compilation for high-speed code execution, including most implementations of Java, together with Microsoft's .NET.
[src:mojo-lang/just-in-time-compilation] Similarly, many regular-expression libraries feature JIT compilation of regular expressions, either to bytecode or to machine code.
[src:mojo-lang/just-in-time-compilation] JIT compilation is also used in some emulators, in order to translate machine code from one CPU architecture to another.
[src:mojo-lang/just-in-time-compilation] A common implementation of JIT compilation is to first have AOT compilation to bytecode (virtual machine code), known as *bytecode compilation*, and then have JIT compilation to machine code (dynamic compilation), rather than interpretation of the bytecode.
[src:mojo-lang/just-in-time-compilation] This improves the runtime performance compared to interpretation, at the cost of lag due to compilation.
[src:mojo-lang/just-in-time-compilation] JIT compilers translate continuously, as with interpreters, but caching of compiled code minimizes lag on future execution of the same code during a given run.
[src:mojo-lang/just-in-time-compilation] Since only part of the program is compiled, there is significantly less lag than if the entire program were compiled prior to execution.
[src:mojo-lang/mojo-manual] Welcome to the Mojo Manual, your guide to the Mojo🔥 programming language.
[src:mojo-lang/mojo-manual] From getting started to advanced systems programming topics, the Mojo Manual helps you write high-performance Mojo code for CPUs and GPUs.
[src:mojo-lang/mojo-manual] If you see anything that can be improved, please file an issue or send a pull request for the docs on GitHub.
[src:mojo-lang/mojo-manual] There's more to explore outside the Mojo Manual.
[src:mojo-lang/mojo-programming-language] Mojo builds on the Multi-Level Intermediate Representation (MLIR) compiler software framework, instead of directly on the lower level LLVM compiler framework like many languages such as Julia, Swift, C++, and Rust.
[src:mojo-lang/mojo-programming-language] It can also often more effectively use certain types of CPU optimizations directly, like single instruction, multiple data (SIMD) with minor intervention by a developer, as occurs in many other languages.
[src:mojo-lang/mojo-programming-language] According to Jeremy Howard of fast.ai, Mojo can be seen as "syntax sugar for MLIR" and for that reason Mojo is well optimized for applications like artificial intelligence (AI).
[src:mojo-lang/mojo-programming-language] The Mojo programming language was created by Modular Inc, which was founded by Chris Lattner, the original architect of the Swift programming language and LLVM, and Tim Davis, a former Google employee.
[src:mojo-lang/mojo-programming-language] The intention behind Mojo is to bridge the gap between Python’s ease of use and the fast performance required for cutting-edge AI applications.
[src:mojo-lang/mojo-programming-language] According to public change logs, Mojo development goes back to 2022.
[src:mojo-lang/mojo-programming-language] In May 2023, the first publicly testable version was made available online via a hosted playground.
[src:mojo-lang/mojo-programming-language] By September 2023 Mojo was available for local download for Linux and by October 2023 it was also made available for download on Apple's macOS.
[src:mojo-lang/mojo-programming-language] The SDK included a command-line driver, a Visual Studio Code extension, and a Jupyter kernel.
[src:mojo-lang/mojo-programming-language] In March 2024, Modular open sourced the Mojo standard library and started accepting community contributions under the Apache 2.0 license.
[src:mojo-lang/mojo-programming-language] In December 2025, Modular published a roadmap toward a 1.0 release, stating that Mojo 1.0 would stabilize core language features and that additional features, such as a match statement and enums, would follow in 1.x releases.
[src:mojo-lang/mojo-programming-language] On May 7, 2026, Modular released Mojo 1.0.0 beta 1 and launched the language's website, mojolang.org.
[src:mojo-lang/mojo-programming-language] Mojo was created for an easy transition from Python.
[src:mojo-lang/mojo-programming-language] The language has syntax similar to Python's, with inferred static typing, and allows users to import Python modules.
[src:mojo-lang/mojo-programming-language] It uses LLVM and MLIR as its compilation backend.
[src:mojo-lang/mojo-programming-language] Mojo programs can import and call Python modules via the CPython runtime, and Mojo functions can be called from Python through C-compatible bindings.
[src:mojo-lang/mojo-programming-language] The language is not source-compatible with Python 3.
[src:mojo-lang/mojo-programming-language] It does not support Python's class system; instead it provides struct types, memory-optimized alternatives to classes that support methods, fields, operator overloading, and decorators.
[src:mojo-lang/mojo-programming-language] Python-style list, set, and dictionary comprehensions are supported.
[src:mojo-lang/mojo-programming-language] The language also provides a borrow checker, an influence from Rust.
[src:mojo-lang/mojo-programming-language] Function arguments are passed as immutable references by default (the read convention).
[src:mojo-lang/mojo-programming-language] Functions may instead declare arguments as mutable references (mut) or take ownership of them, and ownership can be transferred with the ^ operator.
[src:mojo-lang/mojo-programming-language] While the Mojo standard library is open source under the Apache 2.0 license, the compiler is not; Modular has committed to open-sourcing it in fall 2026.
[src:mojo-lang/mojo-programming-language] Mojo supports GPU programming through a gpu package in its standard library.
[src:mojo-lang/mojo-programming-language] Functions in Mojo are declared with def.
[src:mojo-lang/mojo-programming-language] Earlier versions also provided an fn keyword for stricter, statically typed functions; fn was deprecated in 2026 in favor of using def for all functions.
[src:mojo-lang/mojo-programming-language] Mojo originally included a let keyword for immutable bindings; it was removed from the language in 2024.
[src:mojo-lang/mojo-programming-language] Structs are Mojo's compile-time-laid-out alternative to Python classes.
[src:mojo-lang/mojolang-org] Write fast code for diverse hardware, from CPUs to GPUs, without vendor lock-in, in a language that's both user friendly and memory safe.
[src:mojo-lang/mojolang-org] Mojo draws inspiration from the best parts of modern languages - like Python's intuitive syntax, Rust's memory safety, and Zig's powerful and intuitive compile-time metaprogramming.
[src:mojo-lang/mojolang-org] Mojo is built from the ground up to deliver the best performance on the diverse hardware that powers modern AI systems.
[src:mojo-lang/mojolang-org] As a compiled, statically-typed language, it's also ideal for agentic programming.
[src:mojo-lang/mojolang-org] No more choosing between productivity and performance - Mojo gives you both.
[src:mojo-lang/mojolang-org] You can start with simple and familiar programming patterns, and add complexity as you need it.
[src:mojo-lang/mojolang-org] Mojo makes GPU programming accessible to everybody, without vendor-specific libraries and without separately-compiled code.
[src:mojo-lang/mojolang-org] You can finally write high-performance GPU kernels in the same language you use for CPUs.
[src:mojo-lang/mojolang-org] Mojo natively interoperates with Python so you can eliminate performance bottlenecks in existing code without rewriting everything.
[src:mojo-lang/mojolang-org] You can start with one function, and scale up as needed to move performance-critical code into Mojo.
[src:mojo-lang/mojolang-org] Your Mojo code imports naturally into Python and packages together for distribution.
[src:mojo-lang/mojolang-org] Likewise, you can import libraries from the Python ecosystem into your Mojo code.
[src:mojo-lang/mojolang-org] Mojo metaprogramming uses the same language as the run-time code, providing an intuitive system to maximize performance.
[src:mojo-lang/mojolang-org] You can build hardware-specific optimizations with conditional compilation, ensure memory safety with compile-time evaluation, eliminate costly runtime branches, and more—all with clearly defined intentions and zero-cost abstractions.
[src:mojo-lang/mojolang-org] Mojo continues to evolve toward a general-purpose language for high-performance CPU, GPU, and accelerator programming.
[src:mojo-lang/mojolang-org] Implementing the core parser, defining memory types, functions, structs, initializers, argument conventions, and other language foundations.
[src:mojo-lang/mojolang-org] Making Mojo a powerful and expressive language for writing high-performance kernels on CPUs, GPUs, and ASICs, while empowering developers to extend Python seamlessly.
[src:mojo-lang/mojolang-org] Expanding Mojo to support more application-level programming, with a guaranteed memory-safety model and more abstraction features that developers expect for systems programming.
[src:mojo-lang/mojolang-org] Supporting more of Python's dynamic features like classes, inheritance, and untyped variables to maximize compatibility with Python code.
[src:mojo-lang/mojolang-org] The Mojo standard library is fully open-source on GitHub and we welcome contributions!
[src:mojo-lang/mojolang-org] We also plan to open-source the Mojo compiler in 2026.
[src:mojo-lang/mojolang-org] We're committed to open-sourcing all of Mojo, but the language is still very young and we believe a tight-knit group of engineers with a common vision moves faster than a community-driven effort.
[src:mojo-lang/mojolang-org] If you'd like to get involved, join our developer community!
[src:mojo-lang/mojolang-org] Learn Mojo by building the Game of Life.
[src:mojo-lang/mojolang-org] Learn Mojo by solving code problems right in the browser.
[src:mojo-lang/mojolang-org] Learn GPU programming with Mojo by solving puzzles.
[src:mojo-lang/mojolang-org] Ask questions and stay up to date on Mojo ongoings.
[src:mojo-lang/mojolang-org] See upcoming events, meetups, talks, hackathons, and more.
[src:mojo-lang/mojolang-org] Browse open issues, help with docs, and share your projects.
[src:mojo-lang/systems-programming] Systems programming requires a great degree of hardware awareness.
[src:mojo-lang/systems-programming] Its goal is to achieve efficient use of available resources, either because the software itself is performance-critical or because even small efficiency improvements directly transform into significant savings of time or money.
[src:mojo-lang/systems-programming] In systems programming, often limited programming facilities are available.
[src:mojo-lang/systems-programming] The use of automatic garbage collection is not common and debugging is sometimes hard to do.
[src:mojo-lang/systems-programming] The runtime library, if available at all, is usually far less powerful, and does less error checking.
[src:mojo-lang/systems-programming] Because of those limitations, monitoring and logging are often used; operating systems may have extremely elaborate logging subsystems.
[src:mojo-lang/systems-programming] Implementing certain parts in operating systems and networking requires systems programming, for example implementing paging (virtual memory) or a device driver for an operating system.
[src:mojo-lang/systems-programming] Originally systems programmers invariably wrote in assembly language.
[src:mojo-lang/systems-programming] Experiments with hardware support in high level languages in the late 1960s led to such languages as PL/S, BLISS, BCPL, and extended ALGOL for Burroughs Large Systems.
[src:mojo-lang/systems-programming] Forth also has applications as a systems language.
[src:mojo-lang/systems-programming] In the 1970s, C became widespread, aided by the growth of Unix.
[src:mojo-lang/systems-programming] More recently a subset of C++ called Embedded C++ has seen some use, for instance it is used in the I/O Kit drivers of macOS.
[src:mojo-lang/systems-programming] Engineers working at Google created Go in 2007 to address developer productivity in large distributed systems, with developer-focused features such as Concurrency, Garbage Collection, and faster program compilation than C and C++.
[src:mojo-lang/systems-programming] In 2015 Rust came out, a general-purpose programming language often used in systems programming.
[src:mojo-lang/systems-programming] Rust was designed with memory safety in mind and to be as performant as C and C++.
[src:mojo-lang/systems-programming] For historical reasons, some organizations use the term *systems programmer* to describe a job function which would be more accurately termed systems administrator.
[src:mojo-lang/systems-programming] This is particularly true in organizations whose computer resources have historically been dominated by mainframes, although the term is even used to describe job functions which do not involve mainframes.
[src:mojo-lang/systems-programming] This usage arose because administration of IBM mainframes often involved the writing of custom assembler code (IBM's Basic Assembly Language (BAL)), which integrated with the operating system such as OS/MVS, DOS/VSE or VM/CMS.
[src:mojo-lang/systems-programming] Indeed, some IBM software products had substantial code contributions from customer programming staff.
[src:mojo-lang/systems-programming] This type of programming is progressively less common, and increasingly done in C rather than Assembly, but the term *systems programmer* is still used as the de-facto job title for staff administering IBM mainframes even in cases where they do not regularly engage in systems programming activities.
